<h2>Performance in CI/CD Pipelines</h2>

<p>
  CI performance is where package manager choice has the biggest real-world impact. Here are optimized configurations for each tool.
</p>

<h3>npm in CI</h3>

<pre><code set:html=&#123;codeBlock6&#125;></code></pre>

<p>
  Always use <code>npm ci</code> instead of <code>npm install</code> in CI. It's faster because it skips the version resolution step and installs exactly what's in the lock file.
</p>

<h3>pnpm in CI</h3>

<pre><code set:html=&#123;codeBlock7&#125;></code></pre>

<h3>yarn PnP in CI (Zero-Install)</h3>

<pre><code># GitHub Actions example — no install step needed!
- name: Checkout
  uses: actions/checkout@v4

# Dependencies are already in the repo via .yarn/cache
- name: Build
  run: yarn build</code></pre>

<p>
  With yarn's zero-install approach, you skip the install step entirely. This can save 30-60 seconds per CI run. The tradeoff is a larger Git repository due to the committed cache. For detailed CI/CD pipeline optimization strategies, check our guide on <a href="https://devplaybook.cc/blog/best-ci-cd-pipeline-for-small-teams">building the best CI/CD pipeline for small teams</a>.
